section.para:
			A Gazetteer answers three questions about places: which records carry a
			given name, which record a source identifies by its own record id, and which record
			represents a country. Every method may touch backing storage and so may throw
			IOException.
			public interface Gazetteer {

  List<GazetteerEntry> lookup(CharSequence name) throws IOException;

  Optional<GazetteerEntry> byId(String source, String recordId) throws IOException;

  Optional<GazetteerEntry> byRegion(String isoCountryCode) throws IOException;

  Set<String> sources() throws IOException;
}

			A GazetteerEntry is the record of one place. It carries the source it came
			from and that source's record id, the primary name and any alternate names, the location
			as a GeoPoint, the ISO country code, a coarse feature class, a list of the
			identifiers of the places that contain it, and a map of source-specific attributes. The
			GeoPoint holds a latitude and longitude in WGS84 decimal degrees, both
			range-checked when the point is created.
			GeoPoint point = entry.location();
double lat = point.latitude();
double lon = point.longitude();

			Three gazetteer implementations ship with the extension. BundledGazetteer
			is a small worldwide gazetteer packaged with the extension and used through
			getInstance; it needs no external data and is the quickest way to try the
			pipeline. GeoNamesGazetteer reads the GeoNames tab-separated format, and
			OvertureGazetteer reads the Overture division format; both are loaded from a
			file or stream the application supplies.
			// bundled, no external data
Gazetteer bundled = BundledGazetteer.getInstance();

// a downloaded GeoNames table the application supplies
Gazetteer geonames = GeoNamesGazetteer.load(Path.of("allCountries.txt"));

// a downloaded Overture division table
Gazetteer overture = OvertureGazetteer.load(Path.of("divisions.tsv"));
			The GeoNames and Overture data sets are downloaded by the application from their
			publishers and are not distributed with OpenNLP.

			A Geocoder resolves the location mentions in a piece of text against a
			gazetteer. It is given the text and the spans of the mentions, and returns one
			GeoResolution per mention it could resolve.
			public interface Geocoder {

  List<GeoResolution> resolve(CharSequence text, List<Span> locationMentions)
      throws IOException;
}
			A GeoResolution pairs the mention span with the chosen
			GazetteerEntry and a confidence in the choice.
			public record GeoResolution(Span mention, GazetteerEntry entry, double confidence) { }

			Two geocoders ship with the extension, and both take a gazetteer to resolve against.
			PopulationPriorGeocoder chooses each mention independently, preferring the
			most prominent candidate for the name. SpatialCoherenceGeocoder resolves
			the mentions of a document together, preferring a set of choices that sit near one
			another, so the other places named in a document inform each individual choice.
			Gazetteer gazetteer = BundledGazetteer.getInstance();
Geocoder geocoder = new SpatialCoherenceGeocoder(gazetteer);

List<GeoResolution> resolved = geocoder.resolve(text, mentions);

			GeocodeAnnotator runs a geocoder as part of a document pipeline. It reads
			the entity layer produced by the name finder, resolves the location mentions among those
			entities, and provides a locations layer whose annotations carry the full
			GeoResolution for each resolved mention. It requires
			Layers.ENTITIES and provides its own LOCATIONS key.
			Gazetteer gazetteer = BundledGazetteer.getInstance();
Geocoder geocoder = new SpatialCoherenceGeocoder(gazetteer);

DocumentAnalyzer analyzer = DocumentAnalyzer.builder()
    .add(new SentenceDetectorAnnotator(sentenceDetector))
    .add(new TokenizerAnnotator(tokenizer))
    .add(new NameFinderAnnotator(locationFinder))
    .add(new GeocodeAnnotator(geocoder))
    .build();

Document document = analyzer.analyze(text);

for (Annotation<GeoResolution> location : document.get(GeocodeAnnotator.LOCATIONS)) {
  GeoResolution resolution = location.value();
  GeoPoint point = resolution.entry().location();
  System.out.println(resolution.mention().getCoveredText(text)
      + " -> " + resolution.entry().name()
      + " (" + point.latitude() + ", " + point.longitude() + ")");
}

			A resolved place sits inside larger places: a neighborhood inside a city, the city
			inside a state, the state inside a country. A PlaceHierarchy answers, for a
			given place identifier, the chain of places that contain it, nearest first.
			public interface PlaceHierarchy {

  List<PlaceAncestor> ancestors(String id);
}
			Each PlaceAncestor carries the identifier, name, and type of one enclosing
			place, and a ContainmentChain is the ordered list of them from the nearest
			enclosing place out to the largest. The place whose ancestors are requested is not itself
			part of the chain.

ContainmentSpine is a hierarchy built from a table the application supplies. Its builder takes places one at a time, or reads them in bulk from one of two formats. A neutral tab-separated table lists id, parent_id, name, and type per line, with an empty parent for a root; a result exported from a knowledge base that records administrative containment drops straight into this format. A Who's On First meta CSV is read by its own header columns id, parent_id, name, and placetype. // a neutral containment table the application assembles PlaceHierarchy fromTable = ContainmentSpine.builder() .addTable(Path.of("containment.tsv")) .build();
// a Who's On First meta CSV the application downloads PlaceHierarchy fromWof = ContainmentSpine.builder() .addWofMeta(Path.of("whosonfirst-admin-meta.csv")) .build();
// or place by place PlaceHierarchy hierarchy = ContainmentSpine.builder() .add("parkslope", "brooklyn", "Park Slope", "neighbourhood") .add("brooklyn", "nyc", "Brooklyn", "borough") .add("nyc", "nystate", "New York City", "locality") .add("nystate", "usa", "New York", "region") .add("usa", null, "United States", "country") .build(); The identifiers here are the application's own; a real spine uses the identifiers of the source it was built from. Asking for the ancestors of a place returns the enclosing places, nearest first, and not the place itself: for (PlaceAncestor ancestor : hierarchy.ancestors("parkslope")) { System.out.println(ancestor.name()); } prints Brooklyn New York City New York United States As with the large gazetteers, the Who's On First data is downloaded by the application and is not distributed with OpenNLP.

			HierarchyAnnotator adds the containment chain of each resolved place to a
			document. It requires the locations layer produced by the geocoder and provides its own
			CONTAINMENT key, one ContainmentChain per resolved place whose
			identifier the hierarchy knows. It reads the identifier from a gazetteer attribute on the
			resolved entry, by default ATTRIBUTE_KEY_WHOSONFIRST; a second constructor
			takes the attribute key to use, so a spine keyed on another identifier joins on that
			attribute instead.
			DocumentAnalyzer analyzer = DocumentAnalyzer.builder()
    .add(new SentenceDetectorAnnotator(sentenceDetector))
    .add(new TokenizerAnnotator(tokenizer))
    .add(new NameFinderAnnotator(locationFinder))
    .add(new GeocodeAnnotator(geocoder))
    .add(new HierarchyAnnotator(hierarchy))
    .build();

Document document = analyzer.analyze(text);

for (Annotation<ContainmentChain> annotation : document.get(HierarchyAnnotator.CONTAINMENT)) {
  StringBuilder path = new StringBuilder();
  for (PlaceAncestor ancestor : annotation.value().ancestors()) {
    if (path.length() > 0) {
      path.append(" -> ");
    }
    path.append(ancestor.name());
  }
  System.out.println(path);
}
			For a mention resolved to the Park Slope place above, the annotation on the containment
			layer holds that place's enclosing chain, the same
			Brooklyn, New York City, New York, United States that
			ancestors returns; the resolved place itself is not part of the chain. A
			place the hierarchy does not know contributes no annotation, and nothing is invented for
			a missing join.

			Places compare by the cosine of their standardized profiles, in the range minus one to
			one, and mostSimilar ranks the other places by that measure.
			double alike = profiles.similarity("park-slope", "brooklyn-heights");

for (PlaceProfiles.Neighbor neighbor : profiles.mostSimilar("park-slope", 5)) {
  System.out.println(neighbor.id() + "\t" + neighbor.similarity());
}
			The measure is grounded entirely in the supplied metrics, so the quality of the result
			follows the quality of the table. Assembling metric tables from public sources such as
			census and tax data is a data task an application takes on itself; the engine and its
			table format are what the extension provides.
